history.content:
I'm currently taking the class this semester, and I don't think it's very time consuming at all. It is a few chapters of reading from the textbook for each assignment, and you have plenty of time to meet the program / quiz deadlines as long as you keep on track.

As for the topics, I find it pretty interesting to see what you can do in the terminal and the intricacies behind it. The textbook can get a little dense, but I feel that the topics can be very useful. Hope this helps!

children.subject:
Couple of comments

1. It isn't /really/ with Hilfinger, so if you're worried about that, don't worry about it.

2. The way the class works is that you do some reading, finish some assignments, and then go and give quizzes. You can see everything here: http://inst.eecs.berkeley.edu/~selfpace/studyguide/cs9e/

3. FWIW: I think it is quite useful! No, you don't necessarily need to take a class to learn the stuff you learn in CS9E, but it is nice to have a structure in your learning with assignments and quizzes, and tutors to help. 

4. The only thing I'd say is –– do it regularly. It is extremely easy to neglect the class entirely since it is self-paced...
